  <text xml:lang="ta" type="edition">
    <body>
      <div rend="parallel">
        <p xml:id="KT284-kilavi">varaiviṭait tōḻik kiḻattikku uraippāḷāy uraittatu. </p>
        <p xml:lang="en">Told by the confidante as if talking to HER at the time
          of marriage. </p>
      </div>

      <div rend="parallel">
        <lg xml:id="KT284">
          <l> poruta yāṉaip pukarmukaṅ kaṭuppa</l>
          <l> maṉṟat tuṟukaṉ mīmicaip palavuṭa</l>
          <l> ṉoṇceṅ kānta ḷaviḻu nāṭa</l>
          <l> ṉaṟava ṉāyiṉu malla ṉāyiṉu</l>
          <l> nammē cuvarō tammilar kollō</l>
          <l> varaiyiṟ ṟāḻnta vālveḷ ḷaruvi</l>
          <l> koṉṉilaik kurampaiyi ṉiḻitaru</l>
          <l> miṉṉā tiruntavic ciṟukuṭi yōrē.</l>
        </lg>

        <lg xml:lang="en">
          <l rend="indent2">The man from a land, where bright red Malabar lilies open,</l>
          <l rend="indent4">many together, on an elevation of thick stones in the open, <note place="foot"> <term xml:lang="ta"> maṉṟam </term> cannot very well be understood here in its usual sense of "village common". It may also mean "free, open space" – perhaps thus?  </note></l>
          <l rend="indent5">so that it resembles the spotted face of a slain elephant, <note place="foot"> So the stones have blood-red lily spots (the confusion between stones and elephants being a standard comparison).  </note></l>
          <l rend="indent2">whether he is dutiful or not</l>
          <l>are they abusing us,</l>
          <l>the [people] from these little homes to whom it wasn't right, <note place="foot"> That is, what has taken place between HER and the man.</note></l>
          <l rend="indent">where the pure white waterfall hanging down from the mountain</l>
          <l rend="indent2">comes down upon the vainly <note place="foot"> For <term xml:lang="ta"> koṉ </term> cf. note on KT 91.7. One possibility to make sense of <term xml:lang="ta"> koṉ </term> might to apply it adverbially to the leaves, which supposedly cover the huts. So the wild waters will ruin the huts? Cām., on his part, glosses with <term xml:lang="ta"> accattai tarum </term>, "fear-inspiring". </note> leaf[-thatched] huts?</l>
          <l rend="indent4">Do they have nothing [to abuse] themselves [with]? <note place="foot"> <term xml:lang="ta"> tam ilar kollō </term>: this elliptical statement is hard to interpret, but probably it is to be read as a negated parallel construction to <term xml:lang="ta"> nam ēcuvar-ō  </term> with an elliptical verb, meaning that they should mind their own business. </note> </l>

        </lg>
      </div>
    </body>
